Fake It Til You Make It: Rigging the Game with Simulations

Cornerstone #2 - How the World Works

Simulations are an essential part of any data scientist's toolbox. They can be used to solve complex problems or illuminate key concepts. In this project, we'll use simulations for the latter.

The following Coding Section is a core part of this module. After watching the video above, please follow along inside your Companion Workbook.

IMPORTANT: Avoid the urge to copy-paste into your companion workbook. Instead, try to type each piece of code on your own. This will double your engagement with the material. It may feel slower at first, but you'll ultimately master these skills MUCH faster with less back-tracking! Thousands of students have been through this program... it works!

You will also find exercises at the end of your Companion Workbook, which are meant to be completed AFTER the coding section.

 

I. Simulation Methodology¶

Remember how we said that a model is only useful if it can reasonably approximate the "true state of the world" (i.e. the "true underlying relationship" between input features and target variables)?

Well, a simulation helps here because we can actually create the "true underlying relationship." Here's how:

  1. First, we're going to generate an artificial dataset based on a predetermined mapping function.
  • Then, we're going to add noise to that dataset.
  • Next, we can try different models on our artificial dataset.
  • We already know what the "true underlying relationship" should be... it's the mapping function.
  • Finally, we compare how well models of varying complexities separate that signal from the noise.

Let's dive right in.

First, let's import Pandas and NumPy.¶

In [1]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
 

Next, let's import our data visualization libraries.¶

In [2]:
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline

import seaborn as sns
 

Here's what we did:

  • matplotlib is a flexible and powerful tool for visualizing data.
    • From it, we import the pyplot submodule and give it the alias plt.
  • %matplotlib inline tells Jupyter Notebook to plot the charts inside this notebook directly.
  • seaborn provides convenient wrappers on top of matplotlib. It also provides nice styles and themes for our charts.
  • We give it the alias sns

This is the first time we'll use these libraries, so the few modules will also be a gentle introduction to plotting.

 

II. Mapping Function: Sine Wave¶

Just to re-emphasize (because this is important), for our simulation, we are starting with a predetermined mapping function that will serve as the "ground truth" or "true state of the world." Then, we'll be adding artificial noise to it so that we can evaluate how different models perform.

First, our predetermined mapping function is the sine wave.¶

It represents the "true underlying relationship" between input feature xx and target variable yy.

y=sin(x)y=sin(x)

To simulate this function, we'll need two NumPy functions.

The first is the np.linspace() function.¶

  • This function creates an evenly spaced array of numbers between two bounds, so it's useful for simulating an x variable.

For example, this code generates 10 evenly spaced numbers between 1 and 5:

In [3]:
np.linspace(1, 5, 10)
Out[3]:
array([1.        , 1.44444444, 1.88888889, 2.33333333, 2.77777778,
       3.22222222, 3.66666667, 4.11111111, 4.55555556, 5.        ])
 

As you can tell, the first argument to the function gives the starting bound, the second argument gives the ending bound, and the third argument gives the desired length of the sequence. Now, as you'll also notice, the default behavior is to return an inclusive sequence, which means that the starting bound and ending bound are both included in the returned sequence.

So what if you wanted to get an array of numbers evenly spaced by 0.5 apart, then you would actually need to decrease the desired length of the sequence to account for the inclusive ending bound:

In [4]:
# Option 1: Decrease number returned
np.linspace(1, 5, 9)
Out[4]:
array([1. , 1.5, 2. , 2.5, 3. , 3.5, 4. , 4.5, 5. ])
 

For our purposes, we don't care so much about the interval spacing. We're essentially using this sequence of x values to feed into the mapping function and help us plot the function, so we're fine as long as we have enough numbers in the sequence.

We're going to create the x input feature to have 100 numbers between 0 and 2π2π, like so:¶

x = np.linspace(0, 2*np.pi, 100)
In [5]:
# input feature
x = np.linspace(0, 2*np.pi, 100)
 

When running simulations, it's helpful to do a quick sanity check along each step of the setup process, just to make sure you understand what's going on under the hood. Let's display the x values we just generated.

The second function we'll need is the np.sin() function.¶

  • This is a math function for taking the sine of a value.

For example:

In [7]:
np.sin(0)
Out[7]:
0.0
In [8]:
np.sin(1)
Out[8]:
0.8414709848078965
In [9]:
np.sin(np.pi)
Out[9]:
1.2246467991473532e-16
 

Now, if you remember from trigonometry, sin(π)=0sin(π)=0... so what went wrong? Well, nothing went wrong, as it turns out. Because ππ is an irrational number, and thus cannot be represented exactly as a floating point number, np.pi gives you an approximation of pi. Specifically it gives you:

In [10]:
np.pi
Out[10]:
3.141592653589793
 

Thus, when you take np.sin(np.pi), you are actually taking np.sin(3.141592653589793), which gives you a value extreeeeeemely close to 0, but not exactly zero!

In [11]:
np.sin(3.141592653589793)
Out[11]:
1.2246467991473532e-16
 

So for our simulation, we're going to treat np.sin(x) as the "true underlying relationship". Let's plot it.¶

  • Matplotlib pyplot's plot() function is very versatile. To plot xx versus sin(x)sin(x), you can write the following code:
  • Remember, we gave Matplotlib's pyplot module the alias plt.
In [12]:
# Plot x versus sin(x)
plt.plot(x, np.sin(x))
Out[12]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x1a1ee3cda0>]
 
 

Now, one of the best things about the seaborn library is that it makes it very easy to "prettify" your charts without a lot of tweaking and custom code. Specifically, it comes with certain "styles" or themes that you can set.

In [13]:
# Sets the darkgrid theme
sns.set_style('darkgrid')
 

You only need to run this code once per session, and it will change all the plots afterwards. Therefore, in the future, we recommend including that snippet of code at the top of your notebook/script, right after you import the seaborn library. We will adopt that practice going forward as well.

We can copy-paste the exact plotting code we wrote above and see how the theme has changed.¶

  • Tip: There are five preset seaborn themes. They are suited for different applications. Feel free to try them all out in your own notebook: 'darkgrid', 'whitegrid', 'dark', 'white', and 'ticks'
In [14]:
# Plot x versus sin(x)
plt.plot(x, np.sin(x))
Out[14]:

III. Simulating Noise¶

Alright, just to recap: so far, we've looked at the "true" mapping function y=sin(x)y=sin(x) and then introduced a few useful functions. Next, we're going to create the actual simulated dataset with noisy data.

In other words, we want to create the target variable yy as follows:

y=sin(x)+ϵy=sin(x)+ϵ

Where ϵϵ (pronounced "epsilon") is some randomly generated noise that obscures the true underlying signal of the sine mapping function.

NumPy has built-in functions for randomly sampling from common distributions. For example, let's sample from a normal distribution.¶

  • The normal distribution is also known as the Gaussian distribution (or a "bell curve" in laymen's terms).
  • We will use the np.random.normal() function. The first argument is the mean (center) and the second argument is the standard deviation (spread)
In [15]:
# Sample from normal distribution centered at 0
#    and standard deviation of 0.5
np.random.normal(0, 0.5)
Out[15]:
-0.5017154931407191
 

As you're following along in your own workbook, your output will probably be different. That's expected behavior, since we haven't set any random seed yet. In fact, we encourage you to run the above code cell many more times to see a demonstration of different sampled values. To do so, you can click into the cell and then press Control + Enter on your keyboard multiple times.

Next, what if we want to sample more than one value at once?¶

  • No problem. The third argument to np.random.normal() will indicate the number of samples to return.
  • Again, your outputs will likely differ for the following code cell. Try running the next cell multiple times to see how the sampled values change.
In [16]:
# Sample 5 values from normal distribution
np.random.normal(0, 0.5, 5)
Out[16]:
array([ 0.4104196 ,  0.39007244,  0.6571463 , -0.05571082, -0.32652575])
 

In fact, let's plot a sample of 10,000 values to see that "bell curve" in action.¶

  • We will set a random seed with np.random.seed() so that our results can be replicated. We will choose the arbitary seed of 321. You can use any seed you prefer, but we recommend using the same one we chose so that you can follow along.
  • We will use pyplot's hist() function, which plots a histogram. The bins= argument that dictates the number of bins in the histogram.
  • plt.show() effectively hides the "junk"; tip: try running the following cell without plt.show() and see what happens.
In [17]:
# Set seed
np.random.seed(321)

# Normal distribution with mean 0 and stdev 0.5
plt.hist( np.random.normal(0, 0.5, 10000), bins=20 )

# Hides the "junk"
# Tip: try running this cell without plt.show() and see what happens
plt.show()
 
 

A histogram groups values into "buckets" and then plots the number of values in each bucket. So the x-axis marks the bucket boundaries and the y-axis is the "frequency" (i.e. the number of values in that bucket). We don't need to dive into the mechanics of histograms too much right now, but they are useful as a learning tool because they show you the distribution of your values.

As you can see, most of the sampled values fall between -0.5 and 0.5 (i.e. within one standard deviation of the mean; remember: we set the standard deviation to be 0.5).

Alright, let's get back to our simulation. Earlier, we created an input feature xx with 100 values. So now we're going to generate 100 random noise values ϵϵ.¶

  • As a reminder, this is the noisy sine function we are simulating:

y=sin(x)+ϵy=sin(x)+ϵ

In [18]:
# Set seed
np.random.seed(321)

# Generate 100 noise values
noise = np.random.normal(0, .5, 100)
 

Let's take a quick sanity check of what we just created:

IV. Putting It All Together: Noisy Sine Wave¶

So far, we've seen...

  • How to generate an evenly spaced array of input features xx...
  • How to calculate sin(x)sin(x) with NumPy functions...
  • And how to randomly generate a corresponding array of noise values ϵϵ...

Now all that's left is to put it all together to create our target variable y=sin(x)+ϵy=sin(x)+ϵ.

In [20]:
# input feature
x = np.linspace(0, 2*np.pi, 100)

# noise
np.random.seed(321)
noise = np.random.normal(0, .5, 100)

# target variable
y = np.sin(x) + noise
 

Ok, just to recap, let's break down that code.

  • Input feature xx: First, we created an evenly spaced array of 100 numbers from 0 to 2π2π.
x = np.linspace(0, 2*np.pi, 100)
  • Random noise ϵϵ: Next, we generated 100 random numbers from a normal distribution centered at 0.
np.random.seed(321)
noise = np.random.normal(0, .5, 100)
  • Noisy sine wave: Finally, we generated 100 values for the target variable, yy, based on the sin(x)sin(x) function plus the random noise.
y = np.sin(x) + noise

Next, for convenience, let's throw xx and yy into a Pandas DataFrame.¶

  • We'll be saving this dataframe as a CSV file and importing it in the next module.
In [21]:
# Create DataFrame with x and y
df = pd.DataFrame({'x' : x, 'y': y})
df.head()
Out[21]:
  x y
0 0.000000 0.086260
1 0.063467 0.881165
2 0.126933 0.145261
3 0.190400 -0.252824
4 0.253866 -0.320448
 

Save as CSV file without the index.¶

  • If you do not have index=False, then the current index will be saved as its own column, which is unecessary for this exercise.
In [22]:
df.to_csv('simulated_data.csv', index=False)
 

Finally, before moving on, let's plot that dataset first.¶

  • First, we'll use plt.scatter() to plot a scatterplot of the simulated dataset xx and y=sin(x)+ϵy=sin(x)+ϵ.
  • Then, we'll use plt.plot(), which we already introduced earlier, to plot the "true underlying mapping function" y=sin(x)y=sin(x) (without the noise).
    • Tip: color='k' sets the line's color to black.
  • Since we saved x and y in DataFrame df, we can access them with df.x and df.y.

By calling both functions in sequence, we can overlay both plots, like so:

In [23]:
# Scatterplot of x and y
plt.scatter(df.x, df.y)

# Overlay the sine wave
plt.plot(df.x, np.sin(df.x), color='k')

plt.show()
 
 

The smooth black line is the sine wave, which represents the "true underlying relationship" between xx and yy before adding random noise. The blue dots are the 100 simulated data points obtained by first creating a sequence of 100 values of xx and then adding randomly generated noise ϵϵ to form the noisy sine wave y=sin(x)+ϵy=sin(x)+ϵ.
